It is time to revise the relationship between economic growth and sustainable development. We performed optimal curve fitting of these coupling degrees with the SDG Index scores, and the economic, social, and environmental pillar scores (Fig. 3
                        ). The results showed that the degree of coupling of the environmental impact (i.e., score) and economic growth was the main factor affecting the SDG Index scores, economic pillar scores, and social pillar scores, explaining 83%, 52%, and 81% of the total variation, respectively. Moreover, the degree of coupling of the economic impact and economic growth were the main factors affecting the environmental pillar scores, explaining 49% of the variation (Fig. 3). The higher the degree of coupling between the pillars and economic growth, the lower the SDG score. These dynamics were also observed (Fig. 4
                        ) in developed provinces as well as in developing provinces. Generally, the overall progress in achieving SDGs in developed provinces was higher than those in developing provinces. Moreover, we tested the existence of these dynamics with a regression model for individual provinces (Supplementary Statistics) and obtained similar results as those observed across China (Table S3). Regressions between the SDGs and the coupling degrees for each province fell into four response types (bell-shaped, U-shaped, linearly decrease, and not significant). In total, 55%–87% of the provinces show U-shaped relationships, indicating that the achievement of the SDGs increased during the sustainable decoupling of the environmental impact and economic growth.
